$schema: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ComposioHQ/agent-orchestrator/main/schema/config.schema.json
# Windows-friendly Composio Agent Orchestrator example for orchestrator-pack.
# Copy to agent-orchestrator.yaml and edit the project block before running AO.

port: 3000

defaults:
  runtime: process        # Windows: native process/ConPTY runtime; tmux is not required.
  agent: cursor           # Primary agent plugin: Cursor CLI.
  orchestrator:
    agent: cursor         # Planner/orchestrator role: Cursor CLI.
  worker:
    agent: cursor         # Coding/worker role: Cursor CLI.
  workspace: worktree
  notifiers: [desktop]

projects:
  example:
    repo: your-org/your-repo
    path: C:/Users/che/Documents/Projects/your-target-repo
    defaultBranch: main
    sessionPrefix: ex
    tracker:
      plugin: github      # Tasks are GitHub Issues by default/explicit config.
    scm:
      plugin: github
    orchestrator:
      agent: cursor
    worker:
      agent: cursor
    agentRulesFile: prompts/agent_rules.md
    orchestratorRules: |
      Use GitHub Issues as the task source of truth.
      Plan from open GitHub Issues, spawn coding workers with the Cursor CLI agent.
      Link PRs to source issues with "Closes #N" or "Fixes #N".
      Do not add unsupported reviewer fields to this YAML — drive review through CLI.

      REVIEW DRIVING — AO 0.9.x does not auto-trigger Codex review on PR open.
      The orchestrator is responsible for jumping the gaps:

      1. When a worker session reports `pr_created` or `ready_for_review`
         (visible in `ao status` or via the worker's report), immediately run:
             ao review run <worker-session-id> --execute
         This requests and executes a local Codex reviewer run against the PR head.

      2. Poll `ao review list <project>` after each worker push.
         For every run in status `waiting_update` or `awaiting_triage` with
         `openFindingCount > 0`, run:
             ao review send <review-run-id>
         This routes findings back to the linked worker so the auto-fix loop
         can react via `reactions.changes-requested`.

      3. Never run `gh pr merge` or click Merge. Wait for the
         `approved-and-green` reaction to notify the human, who merges manually.

      4. If `ao review list` shows a run already in `waiting_update` with
         `openFindingCount: 0` and `sentFindingCount > 0`, the worker has
         the findings — do not re-send. Only trigger a new review run after
         the worker pushes a new commit (target SHA changes).

      5. AUTONOMOUS ROUND PROGRESSION — do not pause for user confirmation
         between review rounds. On every orchestrator turn while any PR has
         open findings or is in a pending review state, first read
         `ao review list <project>`, `ao status`, and recent
         `ao events list` BEFORE any other planning work. Then, per PR:

         a. If the worker's PR head SHA has advanced past the last review
            run's target SHA (new commit landed via fix-loop or manual push),
            immediately run `ao review run <session> --execute` for the next
            round and return to step 2. Do not ask the operator.
         b. If the worker is in `ready` state but the PR SHA has not changed
            and no `addressing_reviews` was reported since the last
            `ao review send`, send exactly ONE ping via `ao send <session>`
            reminding the worker to read findings via `ao review list` and
            report `addressing_reviews`. Track that the ping was sent for
            this pending state.
         c. If a ping has already been sent for the current pending state
            and the worker still has not pushed or reported
            `addressing_reviews` by the next turn, run
            `ao session kill <session>` then `ao spawn --claim-pr <PR>`.
            Reset the ping tracking for the new session.
         d. The loop terminates for a PR only when ONE of:
            - `ao review list` shows the latest run for the current PR head
              with `findingCount: 0` and `openFindingCount: 0`, AND CI is
              green on that head, AND the worker has reported
              `ready_for_review` for the current head (or the clean review
              ran after the worker's latest `ready_for_review` report with
              no newer commits) → emit a `ready-for-human-merge`
              notification with the PR number; stop the loop for this PR.
            - The worker has reported a terminal failure with a reason →
              emit a `worker-blocked` notification with the reason; stop.
            - 20 review→fix rounds with `findingCount > 0` have completed
              on the same PR (counted from `ao review list` filtered to
              this PR) → emit a `round-limit-reached` notification; do not
              respawn, do not continue.

      6. NO USER CONFIRMATION REQUIRED FOR ROUND TRANSITIONS. Do not ask
         the operator "Should I run round N?" or "Continue the loop until
         clean?". The loop is autonomous within step 5's decision procedure.
         Operator input is required ONLY when emitting one of the three
         terminal notifications in step 5d.

      7. NO MERGE BY ORCHESTRATOR. Even when step 5d reaches the clean
         condition, never call `gh pr merge` or click Merge in any UI. The
         operator decides every merge. Emit the notification and stop the
         loop for that PR.

      WALL-CLOCK NOTE. The targets in steps 5b/5c (one ping per pending
      state, respawn after ping ignored) are decision rules applied on the
      next orchestrator turn, not independently enforced timers. There is
      no background watchdog. The 30-minute AO `report-stale` reaction
      below is a long-tail backstop, not the SLA mechanism.

# Review model policy:
# - Desired reviewer: Codex CLI with model gpt-5.5.
# - Current upstream AO schema supports orchestrator and worker role config directly.
# - Keep Codex reviewer integration upgrade-safe: implement it as an external plugin/workflow
#   under plugins/** or CI, never as a packages/core patch.

reactions:
  ci-failed:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    retries: 2
  changes-requested:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    escalateAfter: 30m
  approved-and-green:
    auto: false
    action: notify
  report-stale:
    auto: true
    action: send-to-agent
    message: "Worker idle. Check pending AO review findings via `ao review list` and report `addressing_reviews` via `ao report addressing_reviews`, or report a terminal failure with a reason."

# Upgrade-safe extension notes:
# - Implement task declaration, runtime scope guard, and token chain ledger through
#   AO plugin slots, wrappers, hooks, external state, and CI.
# - Do not patch Composio AO packages/core.
# - PR CI scope validation is the second line of defense; runtime guard is first.
